node.text:
I don’t think I’m going to say it much better than @maddyfurgiuele on Twitter

It’s a reminder we want to shout from the rooftops every single day, not just in September….. please STAY. - @therealjoirizarry 

@mentalhealthwmaddy
•
suicide prevention month is a great way to bring awareness to a topic that is often avoided in our daily lives. but the reality is, suicide exists every month whether we like it or not. here are some of the key signs to look out for if someone in your life is contemplating suicide.
• irritability 
• mood swings
• giving away belongings
• suddenly happy 
• talks about death/dying (this includes saying ‘kms’)
• no longer engaging in activities they normally liked
• decreased performance in school

now we know the warning signs. what happens next? tomorrow i’ll be posting ways you can help.

node.text:
TW: Suicide 

Therapy has saved my life. A few years ago I had to check myself into a mental health hospital because I was actively suicidal and got caught in the middle of an attempt. I got scooped up by an ambulance and taken to JPS in Fort Worth before being taken to Mesa Springs. I was a mess, just recently divorced, heavy drug problems, and literally everything that could go wrong that was self inflicted was going wrong. I was in the worst spot I’ve ever been in, and was hurting more than I could even imagine. When I first got to Mesa Springs I didn’t buy into all the things that were going on, would skip classes, or basically anything to do the bare minimum. The turning point for my stay and my life to get to the point where I was at now was the question “is this how you want your daughter to remember you” and those words rang so loudly in my head…so basically after that conversation with the person I shared a room with I turned it around. I bought into the healing process and allowed for the methods I was being taught to better myself, and by doing that I got better. I worked on who I was and dealt with the demons that were causing me so much despair…my mental health was now manageable by the time I left that place. It wasn’t always fun and the self work the therapist there put me through helped. I’m not ashamed that I had to go to the hospital, I needed that. I’m telling my story during #suicideawarenessmonth so more people know they aren’t alone in the process and that it does get better in time. Not everyone’s story will look like this but we want to help in any way we can to ensure no person feels alone in their journey. I am a survivor. - @tanner_hamilton22 
.

.

node.text:
"Today was a Difficult Day," said Pooh.

There was a pause.

"Do you want to talk about it?" asked Piglet.

"No," said Pooh after a bit. "No, I don't think I do."

"That's okay," said Piglet, and he came and sat beside his friend.

"What are you doing?" asked Pooh.

"Nothing, really," said Piglet. "Only, I know what Difficult Days are like. I quite often don't feel like talking about it on my Difficult Days either.

"But goodness," continued Piglet, "Difficult Days are so much easier when you know you've got someone there for you. And I'll always be here for you, Pooh."

And as Pooh sat there, working through in his head his Difficult Day, while the solid, reliable Piglet sat next to him quietly, swinging his little legs...he thought that his best friend had never been more right."

A.A.Milne ❤️

If you’re having a Difficult Day, please know you are not alone.  You are seen and you are heard and you are supported. - @therealjoirizarry

node.text:
TW: Death/Suicide

The life I have today, the good days outweigh the bad days.

Full disclosure after my son died from suicide 11 years ago I wanted to die everyday for three years straight. I was an active alcoholic and buried deep in grief.  Once I almost completed the act. 

Fast forward to today, I’m no longer active in my alcoholism and my family’s grief and trauma and loss has been used to advocate mental health awareness. This is our story. 

Everyday won’t be a good day, and the bad days might outweigh the good ones, but please for the love of yourself and your friends and family…… STAY. 

In the month of September this will be our forever message. We can’t change our past (suicide loss) but maybe we can help you see a brighter future for yourself. 

#nationalsuicideawareness 

- @therealjoirizarry 

📸 nfronkinstein on Twitter

node.text:
This is me 100%…like I’m joking but I’m not lol. I take mental health serious but sometimes my brain can be so ridiculous that I have to ask myself “what the fuck” lol. Anyone else feel this way? Life has gotten way better, and that’s the one thing that sticks with me. It may take a long time, it may feel like it never will but it does get better eventually. I’m proud of you for continuing to fight. - @tanner_hamilton22

node.text:
This…hit home for me. I have gotten better as noticing the signs of when I’m heading down the rabbit hole so to speak and I’ve come up with some healthy coping mechanism that work for me like practicing self care and walking away from situations that no longer serve me. I remember this feeling so well and I wanted to see if anyone has gone through this as well. If you have, you are a strong and beautiful person deserving of all the love. - @tanner_hamilton22

Or maybe it’s because the worlds on fire 🔥 pandemics and hurricanes and political unrest? 

IDK, but I’m trying to put my head back on straight. Can anyone share a positive thought 💭 I can use to brighten my day? - @therealjoirizarry
